WEBVTT

00:00:03.569 --> 00:00:05.370
As a cook and writer,

00:00:05.370 --> 00:00:09.089
I have long liked the tastes and smells

00:00:09.089 --> 00:00:11.449
of Middle Eastern food. 

00:00:11.449 --> 00:00:16.609
It is one of the oldest and most important ways of cooking in the world. 

00:00:16.609 --> 00:00:18.530
Now I want to learn more. 

00:00:20.010 --> 00:00:22.809
You know, there is only one true way

00:00:22.809 --> 00:00:26.489
to learn about a place's food, and that is to go there. 

00:00:26.489 --> 00:00:30.850
To eat the food with the people who cook it and eat it each day. 

00:00:30.850 --> 00:00:34.570
That way, it tastes like the place. 

00:00:34.570 --> 00:00:38.609
You can taste the land, the way they live, and old ways. 

00:00:38.609 --> 00:00:42.170
That is so good. So come with me on my trip. 

00:00:42.170 --> 00:00:44.450
Can I look in your cupboard? 

00:00:44.450 --> 00:00:49.049
We will find foods and ways to cook that show what three lands

00:00:49.049 --> 00:00:51.729
with fun food stories are like. 

00:00:51.729 --> 00:00:53.810
Cheese and roses, it should not work! 

00:00:53.810 --> 00:00:57.609
These places are seen as the main parts of Middle Eastern food. 

00:00:59.289 --> 00:01:02.369
My trip takes me across North Iran

00:01:02.369 --> 00:01:05.650
to taste Persian foods with a long past. 

00:01:05.650 --> 00:01:10.409
Then to Lebanon with its Arab tastes from the Levant. 

00:01:10.409 --> 00:01:14.930
And to Turkey, where ways to cook from many kinds of land

00:01:14.930 --> 00:01:16.650
have gone all over the world. 

00:01:16.650 --> 00:01:20.010
I made a date shape - I should have made a walnut shape. 

00:01:20.010 --> 00:01:21.969
I want to find new tastes. 

00:01:21.969 --> 00:01:25.090
This takes me through old and pretty lands. 

00:01:25.090 --> 00:01:28.010
But, more key, into people's homes. 

00:01:28.010 --> 00:01:31.329
I loved it so much, and I thank you very much. 

00:01:31.329 --> 00:01:34.890
This is my chance to learn new ways to cook and new dishes

00:01:34.890 --> 00:01:36.329
that are not in books. 

00:01:36.329 --> 00:01:38.810
But have been passed down for many years. 

00:01:38.810 --> 00:01:42.129
How long does it take you? 

Five minutes.
Five minutes?

00:01:42.129 --> 00:01:44.450
Well, I should hurry up then. 

00:01:44.450 --> 00:01:47.450
And I will share the secrets I find

00:01:47.450 --> 00:01:50.489
by cooking foods that my trip made me think of. 

00:01:50.489 --> 00:01:54.090
This time, I go to a land that is changing fast. 

00:01:54.090 --> 00:01:56.730
From the foods of Ottoman kings' homes

00:01:56.730 --> 00:01:58.689
to the plain home cooking

00:01:58.689 --> 00:02:00.450
at the heart of Turkey. 

00:02:06.450 --> 00:02:10.810
I start in Istanbul, where 15 million people live. 

00:02:10.810 --> 00:02:14.250
Today, it is a city that changes fast and does well. 

00:02:14.250 --> 00:02:17.250
It sits in both Europe and Asia. 

00:02:28.569 --> 00:02:32.569
It used to be called Constantinople, the center of the Ottoman rule. 

00:02:32.569 --> 00:02:36.169
From here, rich kings ruled over big parts of Europe,

00:02:36.169 --> 00:02:38.969
Asia, and North Africa. 

00:02:38.969 --> 00:02:43.050
They brought tastes from far lands back to their palace kitchens 

00:02:43.050 --> 00:02:46.930
to make the world's most fancy food of that time. 

00:02:56.009 --> 00:03:01.169
One of Istanbul's best hotels was once a king's palace. 

00:03:01.169 --> 00:03:03.930
You can see how grand and rich it is. 

00:03:03.930 --> 00:03:06.930
You can see it not just in its lights and stone,

00:03:06.930 --> 00:03:11.129
but also in the old Ottoman foods it makes. 

00:03:16.569 --> 00:03:18.289
When the Empire was at its best,

00:03:18.289 --> 00:03:21.370
the best cooks were called from far places 

00:03:21.370 --> 00:03:24.569
to try new foods and ways to cook, 

00:03:24.569 --> 00:03:27.849
to make foods good enough for the king's table. 

00:03:33.650 --> 00:03:38.210
A whole fish baked in salt would have been a real show. 

00:03:38.210 --> 00:03:41.930
At that time, salt was a very special thing all over the world. 

00:03:46.409 --> 00:03:48.370
You...

00:03:48.370 --> 00:03:52.090
This is the king showing off. 

00:03:52.090 --> 00:03:56.930
It is the idea of a silver plate being shown to your guests 

00:03:56.930 --> 00:04:00.210
with a big, whole fish baked in shiny salt. 

00:04:01.810 --> 00:04:04.330
It is as much about show as it is about taste. 

00:04:12.090 --> 00:04:14.289
It is so good. 

00:04:14.289 --> 00:04:17.370
It is so good...
but the point of this food is the place. 

00:04:17.370 --> 00:04:20.410
It is about how fancy and how nice the room is. 

00:04:20.410 --> 00:04:22.410
It is about the very nice plates. 

00:04:22.410 --> 00:04:24.569
It is about how the food is shown. 

00:04:25.889 --> 00:04:27.170
This is fancy food. 

00:04:27.170 --> 00:04:30.089
It is fun and it IS about a show. 

00:04:36.290 --> 00:04:41.490
Baklava - the sticky, sweet cake loved all over the world - 

00:04:41.490 --> 00:04:44.649
was one more food made perfect for the king to enjoy. 

00:04:49.689 --> 00:04:55.410
40 very thin layers of pastry put with small cut nuts 

00:04:55.410 --> 00:05:00.050
and sweet syrup on top made each bite a food art piece. 

00:05:02.689 --> 00:05:05.930
Even now, the new bakers must work in the kitchen 

00:05:05.930 --> 00:05:10.209
for at least five years before they can touch the pastry. 

00:05:10.209 --> 00:05:11.689
Thank you. 

00:05:11.689 --> 00:05:15.050
And there is also an art to eating it. 

00:05:15.050 --> 00:05:17.490
You check that it is gold. 

00:05:17.490 --> 00:05:21.490
You put your fork in and then cut all the way with a knife. 

00:05:21.490 --> 00:05:23.529
If you turn it upside down, 

00:05:23.529 --> 00:05:27.449
no drop of syrup should fall off it. 

00:05:27.449 --> 00:05:31.209
Then you dip it into your thick, rich yogurt. 

00:05:31.209 --> 00:05:33.610
That is the crust on the top of the yogurt. 

00:05:33.610 --> 00:05:36.449
And then into the ground nut pieces. 

00:05:36.449 --> 00:05:39.009
And then you put it in your mouth upside down, 

00:05:39.009 --> 00:05:42.050
so that the last layer of pastry, which has the most butter... 

00:05:43.290 --> 00:05:45.610
just touches the top of your mouth. 

00:05:50.329 --> 00:05:52.649
You need to try a bit to eat it well. 

00:05:54.050 --> 00:05:55.850
But it is very, very good. 

00:05:55.850 --> 00:05:58.009
It is not too much sweet. 

00:05:58.009 --> 00:06:01.209
It has nuts and is flaky and light. 

00:06:01.209 --> 00:06:02.610
This is lovely. 

00:06:05.649 --> 00:06:09.649
While the kings were eating fine foods from all over the world, 

00:06:09.649 --> 00:06:13.329
most of the land was eating plain home-cooked foods 

00:06:13.329 --> 00:06:16.569
made with things from its many kinds of land. 

00:06:18.449 --> 00:06:20.529
I am going to a lokanta. 

00:06:20.529 --> 00:06:24.170
It is a cafe like a lunch room, liked all over Turkey. 

00:06:24.170 --> 00:06:28.569
It gives home-style lunches to people who work in the city. 

00:06:28.569 --> 00:06:33.490
It is also where I will meet my helper and talker for my trip, 

00:06:33.490 --> 00:06:34.930
Sibel Samli. 

00:06:35.930 --> 00:06:37.490
Hey, Nigel. 

00:06:37.490 --> 00:06:39.050
I am liking this place. 

00:06:40.250 --> 00:06:41.689
Welcome. 
Wow.

00:06:42.810 --> 00:06:47.649
A long time ago, Turkey did not have many food places. 

00:06:47.649 --> 00:06:50.449
But just over 100 years ago, the lokanta, 

00:06:50.449 --> 00:06:54.250
with its home recipes and warm, nice feel, 

00:06:54.250 --> 00:06:56.129
came out as one new kind. 

00:06:57.329 --> 00:07:01.970
And are now one of its food places that has stayed the longest. 

00:07:01.970 --> 00:07:04.329
So, tell me, what is here? 

00:07:04.329 --> 00:07:08.129
OK, so this is a normal weekday lunch 

00:07:08.129 --> 00:07:12.250
for anyone who works and lives in Istanbul. 

00:07:12.250 --> 00:07:15.889
And do I pick one thing or a few things? 

00:07:15.889 --> 00:07:20.290
How does it work? 
Well, Turks usually do not think a meal is a meal

00:07:20.290 --> 00:07:22.610
if it does not have meat in it. 

00:07:22.610 --> 00:07:25.089
I mean, there are a lot of greens, for sure. 

00:07:25.089 --> 00:07:28.410
Green beans, you will have a lot of potato and meat mixed. 

00:07:28.410 --> 00:07:30.930
Peas, green squash, beans. 

00:07:30.930 --> 00:07:32.730
But then you also have lamb, beef. 

00:07:33.930 --> 00:07:36.649
This is what I call comfort food. 

00:07:36.649 --> 00:07:40.769
You know, lots of juices, lots of tastes and juices. 

00:07:42.610 --> 00:07:44.970
This is food cooked for a long time, 

00:07:44.970 --> 00:07:49.370
given fast and with no fuss to hungry people who come often 

00:07:49.370 --> 00:07:51.569
at plain tables shared with others. 

00:07:53.250 --> 00:07:58.730
It is very plain, but it is a very nice thing to be able to walk in, 

00:07:58.730 --> 00:08:03.250
eat fresh, warm food in 30 minutes 

00:08:03.250 --> 00:08:05.569
and go back to work. 

00:08:05.569 --> 00:08:07.290
And not too much money, I think. 

00:08:07.290 --> 00:08:09.449
Yes, very. 
Shall we sit down.

00:08:12.329 --> 00:08:15.170
The way of going out at lunch for a sandwich - 

00:08:15.170 --> 00:08:17.009
is that here? 
Mm-mm.

00:08:17.009 --> 00:08:20.649
I think everyone would be very mad if anyone ever said 

00:08:20.649 --> 00:08:23.370
that they had to have sandwiches for lunch. 

00:08:24.850 --> 00:08:27.970
Most workers will stop for lunch 

00:08:27.970 --> 00:08:30.410
and come to a food place like this. 

00:08:30.410 --> 00:08:34.289
You find kinds of it in the most fancy area 

00:08:34.289 --> 00:08:37.129
and the most poor area. 

00:08:37.129 --> 00:08:39.649
They are all...
Because they will all cook the same foods. 

00:08:39.649 --> 00:08:42.929
It is kind of like a part of home, in a way. 

00:08:42.929 --> 00:08:44.929
Yes, yes. 

00:08:44.929 --> 00:08:46.809
This is so, so good. 

00:08:46.809 --> 00:08:48.090
And no sandwiches! 

00:08:48.090 --> 00:08:49.769
Food like this each day. 

00:08:49.769 --> 00:08:52.649
Yes, it is so, so good. 

00:08:52.649 --> 00:08:55.090
This food is just what I like. 

00:08:55.090 --> 00:08:59.169
Good foods that do not need to be loud or show off, 

00:08:59.169 --> 00:09:01.409
but just go well together. 

00:09:01.409 --> 00:09:05.529
Plain home cooking with soft, warm tastes. 

00:09:05.529 --> 00:09:08.370
The kind of food I like to make at home. 

00:09:12.009 --> 00:09:13.649
Cut an onion into rough bits 

00:09:13.649 --> 00:09:17.570
with some red and yellow peppers. 

00:09:17.570 --> 00:09:19.129
Add to a big baking pan. 

00:09:20.450 --> 00:09:23.370
Pick some tomatoes 

00:09:23.370 --> 00:09:25.929
and add a few bits of thyme. 

00:09:25.929 --> 00:09:28.929
Put olive oil on the mix and then bake. 

00:09:31.049 --> 00:09:35.289
After 50 minutes, add butter beans, a good bit of allspice, 

00:09:35.289 --> 00:09:37.370
and put back in the oven for ten minutes. 

00:09:39.889 --> 00:09:44.649
Quickly boil green beans in salt water and then put in cold water. 

00:09:44.649 --> 00:09:46.169
This keeps them bright. 

00:09:47.450 --> 00:09:51.330
Mix in the beans at the last minute, so they just get warm, 

00:09:51.330 --> 00:09:52.649
and then serve. 

00:09:53.970 --> 00:09:57.970
Plain stews like this are, for me, the real taste of Turkey. 

00:09:57.970 --> 00:09:59.730

00:09:09.730 --> 01:00:04.210
They come from the good soil of its farm land 

00:10:04.210 --> 00:10:06.250
in middle Anatolia. 

00:10:06.250 --> 00:10:10.129
This big area is east of Istanbul - Asian Turkey. 

00:10:11.570 --> 00:10:13.809
And it is where my trip goes on. 

00:10:15.889 --> 00:10:20.169
Some think this is where growing plants first started. 

00:10:20.169 --> 00:10:24.570
Many foods, not just Turkish, can be from Anatolia. 

00:10:24.570 --> 00:10:27.529
And the land is one of few in the world 

00:10:27.529 --> 00:10:31.649
with enough different kinds and amounts of food to feed itself. 

00:10:34.090 --> 00:10:36.809
Many of its people still live near the land, 

00:10:36.809 --> 00:10:39.049
as they have for hundreds of years. 

00:10:55.289 --> 00:10:59.090
It is early morning in the Develi area of middle Anatolia, 

00:10:59.090 --> 00:11:02.330
and the old morning work starts once more. 

00:11:04.730 --> 00:11:08.970
Songul has left the town only one time in her whole life. 

00:11:12.850 --> 00:11:16.889
THEY SPEAK THEIR OWN WORDS

00:11:18.929 --> 00:11:20.929
Nigel, Songul. 
I am Nigel.

00:11:29.970 --> 00:11:32.529
She says there is more in the back room, too. 

00:11:36.370 --> 00:11:39.090
They finish this in the summer and then make it again. 

00:11:39.090 --> 00:11:42.409
This and next door will last for about six months. 

00:11:43.490 --> 00:11:47.409
This is the kept kind of a thin, flat bread with no yeast, 

00:11:47.409 --> 00:11:51.129
yufka, liked all through Turkey. 
It is hard to not eat. 

00:11:51.129 --> 00:11:52.730
Once baked, it has very little water. 

00:11:57.409 --> 00:11:59.809
This means that it can be kept for months 

00:11:59.809 --> 00:12:02.490
and then made wet again when it is needed. 

00:12:03.889 --> 00:12:09.289
Wheat was first grown in Turkey about 10,000 years ago. 

00:12:09.289 --> 00:12:12.889
And the first breads most likely looked a lot like this. 

00:12:12.889 --> 00:12:14.289
It is like a piece of art! 

00:12:14.289 --> 00:12:15.769
LAUGHING

00:12:15.769 --> 00:12:17.450
It is just, it is pretty. 

00:12:19.570 --> 00:12:23.529
Songul has said she will show me how they make one of their main foods, 

00:12:23.529 --> 00:12:25.090
manti. 

00:12:26.730 --> 00:12:29.169
Manti starts with a plain dough 

00:12:29.169 --> 00:12:32.129
made from flour, water, salt and eggs. 

00:12:32.129 --> 00:12:36.809
While Songul mixes and rolls the dough, her son's wife 

00:12:36.809 --> 00:12:42.490
makes the inside part from ground beef, onions, plants and ground cumin. 

00:12:44.129 --> 00:12:47.169
It is easy to see that this food has been made many times. 

00:12:47.169 --> 00:12:49.330
These ladies are very good at it. 

00:12:49.330 --> 00:12:51.129
Ah, OK, into long bits. 

00:12:53.090 --> 00:12:54.889
So, she is saying, mostly, 

00:12:54.889 --> 00:12:57.730
her older sister lives in Ankara, the main city, 

00:12:57.730 --> 00:13:00.730
and she is saying that her older sister says that there is a machine 

00:13:00.730 --> 00:13:03.330
that cuts now, so they should buy that, 

00:13:03.330 --> 00:13:06.529
and she is saying we are not lazy city people, 

00:13:06.529 --> 00:13:09.570
we are town people, and we are used to doing it. 

00:13:09.570 --> 00:13:11.409
And then a little bit of meat. 

00:13:14.090 --> 00:13:16.169
How much? In the middle. 

00:13:18.450 --> 00:13:21.889
How manti made new foods like ravioli 

00:13:21.889 --> 00:13:23.610
is easy to see. 

00:13:23.610 --> 00:13:25.210
And then like that? 

00:13:27.450 --> 00:13:29.769
Can you think how long you would have to wait for food 

00:13:29.769 --> 00:13:30.889
if I made it. 

00:13:37.730 --> 00:13:41.250
It is not long before the talk turns away 

00:13:41.250 --> 00:13:42.690
from the cooking. 

00:13:44.809 --> 00:13:48.730
So she says she was in love with Songul's son, 

00:13:48.730 --> 00:13:52.529
but because they thought her dad would not let her get married 

00:13:52.529 --> 00:13:58.009
to him, they ran away to Ankara, to the aunt's house, 

00:13:58.009 --> 00:14:00.570
and then they stayed there for three days 

00:14:00.570 --> 00:14:03.690
until the groups agreed on the wedding. 

00:14:05.610 --> 00:14:08.289
It happens a lot in this town, 

00:14:08.289 --> 00:14:12.929
because if they are in love, but the family has other plans, 

00:14:12.929 --> 00:14:14.450
then the girls just run away. 

00:14:20.850 --> 00:14:23.289
Making the food with Songul is fun. 

00:14:24.529 --> 00:14:28.809
Manti is boiled and its sauce is made by grating garlic 

00:14:28.809 --> 00:14:30.730
into home-made yogurt. 

00:14:32.970 --> 00:14:36.009
And a time for me to find out how Songul feels 

00:14:36.009 --> 00:14:38.690
about life here on the Anatolian flat land. 

00:14:40.529 --> 00:14:44.690
This seems like a hard way to live. 

00:14:44.690 --> 00:14:48.769
I am just asking, would you like to work... 

00:14:49.769 --> 00:14:51.169
an easier job in the city. 

00:15:00.210 --> 00:15:01.409
Yes, it is home. 

00:15:02.490 --> 00:15:06.009
So, do you think that your kids, and your grandson too, 

00:15:06.009 --> 00:15:09.809
do you think that they will live this way later. 

00:15:27.769 --> 00:15:32.009
The sad thing about that is that maybe this farm would not be here 

00:15:32.009 --> 00:15:34.850
if it is not given to new young people. 

00:15:37.289 --> 00:15:38.929
It is easy for me 

00:15:38.929 --> 00:15:42.529
to talk about keeping an old way of life. 

00:15:42.529 --> 00:15:46.009
Making your own yogurt and your own cheese 

00:15:46.009 --> 00:15:48.250
and having a cow in the yard. 

00:15:48.250 --> 00:15:49.929
But this is hard. 

00:15:49.929 --> 00:15:52.009
This is staying alive. 

00:15:52.009 --> 00:15:55.210
This is very, very needed for their lives. 

00:16:03.769 --> 00:16:08.330
The hot food bits are topped with some of the garlic yogurt 

00:16:08.330 --> 00:16:13.529
and then smoked, sweet, crushed red peppers 

00:16:13.529 --> 00:16:15.490
warmed in olive oil. 

00:16:15.490 --> 00:16:16.690
This is so good. 

00:16:22.049 --> 00:16:24.730
You know, there is nothing that means more to me... 

00:16:26.049 --> 00:16:28.490
than sharing food. 

00:16:28.490 --> 00:16:31.289
And that someone shares their food with me... 

00:16:32.370 --> 00:16:33.929
is everything. 

00:16:33.929 --> 00:16:37.730
But also, to share their skill, 

00:16:37.730 --> 00:16:39.809
their smarts, what they know. 

00:16:39.809 --> 00:16:42.210
They have also shared their way of life. 

00:16:42.210 --> 00:16:44.330
It just makes me... 

00:16:44.330 --> 00:16:46.009
just so, so happy. 

00:17:01.809 --> 00:17:04.970
My looking into Anatolian food goes on 

00:17:04.970 --> 00:17:09.849
50 miles west of Develi in the cool land of Cappadocia. 

00:17:14.009 --> 00:17:16.609
It has homes cut in rock, 

00:17:16.609 --> 00:17:20.329
fun rock shapes and old grape fields. 

00:17:21.609 --> 00:17:24.369
Once a hidden nice place in nature, 

00:17:24.369 --> 00:17:26.369
this is now a World Old Place site 

00:17:26.369 --> 00:17:29.849
and one of Turkey's most liked spots for people to visit. 

00:17:38.089 --> 00:17:43.410
I am here to learn more about the old store food pekmez, 

00:17:43.410 --> 00:17:48.450
a grape sweet stuff used a lot in both sweet and not sweet foods. 

00:17:50.970 --> 00:17:54.089
So I have come to meet Faruk at his family grape field. 

00:17:56.650 --> 00:17:59.890
So, how long have grapes grown on this land? 

00:18:01.049 --> 00:18:04.650
Many, many years, these kinds of grapes are here. 

00:18:04.650 --> 00:18:07.450
But this garden, from my grandpa. 

00:18:07.450 --> 00:18:08.609
This is the most... 

00:18:09.890 --> 00:18:11.609
sweetest one. 

00:18:11.609 --> 00:18:13.289
These have all been growing... 

00:18:14.329 --> 00:18:16.049
without giving any water. 

00:18:25.410 --> 00:18:29.849
Times are changing, and these days Faruk is one of few local people 

00:18:29.849 --> 00:18:32.170
still making his own pekmez. 

00:18:34.450 --> 00:18:38.569
So, you must have seen a lot of change around here. 

00:18:38.569 --> 00:18:39.890
Yes, for sure. 

00:18:41.450 --> 00:18:46.890
When I was a kid, we had more trees and more green things. 

00:18:48.130 --> 00:18:51.009
Just like this. 
All places were like this. 

00:18:51.009 --> 00:18:52.690
No one is looking after it. 

00:18:54.210 --> 00:18:55.849
Why is no one looking after it? 

00:18:55.849 --> 00:19:00.849
They are running hotels or different kinds of visit places. 

00:19:00.849 --> 00:19:04.769
It is more easy for them to make life like that. 

00:19:06.289 --> 00:19:09.490
And the people visiting are hurting all the land. 

